<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Evelyn Cisneros, Wendy Van Dyck in S.F. Ballet's 'Minuetto'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  DANCE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Sforzando! -- As with every other arts organization in the city, San Francisco
Ballet is readying itself for June's Mozart &amp; His Time festival.;    Resident
choreographer Val Caniparoli will create a pas de deux for Evelyn Cisneros and
Anthony Randazzo, set to the slow movement of Mozart's final piano concerto.
And artistic director Helgi Tomasson plans a new ballet to the "Haffner"
Symphony. The program, June 25 and 27 in the War Memorial Opera House, also
will include Tomasson's "Menuetto," set to a series of Mozart contredanses.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.F. BALLET PREPARES FOR MOZART FESTIVAL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Dance  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But all this still isn't enough to fill an evening, and the company is
looking about for another work to perform. There's an excellent one already in
its repertory, "Mozart C Minor Mass," one of the strongest pieces ever made by
former artistic director Michael Smuin. However, relations between Smuin and
the ballet being what they are (chilly), it probably won't be considered.;   
In other SFB news: Newly promoted principal dancer Shannon Lilly is making
ready for her debut as Princess Aurora in "Sleeping Beauty," partnered by Yuri
Zhukov. If last year's procedure is any indication, she will dance it at the
May 4 matinee.;    MOZARTIANA -- This, the title of one of George Balanchine's
loveliest ballets, is a short-lived but functional heading for news of the
upcoming Mozart festival in San Francisco.;    Besides SFB, other dance
organizations participating include:;    (box) Dance Through Time, presenting
dances of Mozart's day in period costumes, accompanied by the Magnificat
Baroque Orchestra. May 17 and 24.;    (box) San Francisco Institute of
Choreography. Anthology program of new work to Mozart's music. June 8-9.;   
(box) 1800 Sq. Feet. Experimental work by High Risk Group, Hank Hyena, Julie
Queen and Circus Absurdus. High Risk's "Mozart Projects" is based on the
Requiem. Also includes the exhibit you won't see at any Bay Area museum,
"Austrian Undergarments of the Late 18th Century." June 7-8.;    (box)
Goethe-Institut. "Puer Aeternus" ("Eternal Boy"), a dance-theater piece by
Kathryn Roszak with San Francisco Opera Center singers. June 6.;    (box)
Theater Artaud Collective. "The Kiss," a dance-theater piece by Douglas
Rosenberg's Dziga Vertov Performance Group (cognoscenti will know its
namesake, an experimental Russian film-maker of the early Stalinist years)
with dancer Nancy Karp. June 27-28. Works by Nancy Lee's Li Chiao-Ping Dance
and Chopsticks &amp; Sneakers, from Los Angeles. June 29-30.;    For a brochure of
the entire festival, which begins in May with museum exhibits and American
Conservatory Theater's production of Beaumarchais' "The Marriage of Figaro,"
and ends in July with the traditional Midsummer Mozart Festival, call the San
Francisco Symphony box office, (415) 431-5400.;    COMIN' UP -- Ruth Langridge
Dance Company comes down from Belvedere (Marin County) for its annual San
Francisco season, 8 p.m. Thursday-Saturday at New Performance Gallery, 3153
17th St. It features a new work by John Malashock of San Diego, a rising
talent, and "To Your Credit" by Christopher Pilafian, a satire on our plastic
economy. Tickets: $12, (415) 863-9834.;    Deborah Slater emulates Noel Coward
in "Experiments for Living," 8:30 p.m. Wednesday-Saturday and 3 p.m. Sunday at
Studio 210, 3435 Army St. (at Valencia), San Francisco. Tickets: $8, (415)
824-2464.  </TEXT>
